Poll Voting Platform
Overview

This project is a paid, public poll voting platform built to allow users to buy votes for nominees across one or more polls in a secure, auditable, and scalable way. The platform uses Paystack for payment collection, Oracle Database for persistence, NestJS for the backend API, and Next.js for the frontend experience.

The system is intentionally designed so that payment success is not trusted from the browser. The browser can start a payment, but only the backend webhook is allowed to finalize votes. This makes the platform resilient against duplicate submissions, browser tampering, and payment spoofing.

At its core, the platform solves five major problems well:

collecting paid votes across multiple polls

applying votes only after verified payment

preventing duplicate application of the same payment

generating immutable receipts and PDFs

giving admins controlled operational visibility without exposing sensitive internals

Business Purpose

The application is meant for monetized public polling, where each vote has a price. A user can browse active polls, choose a nominee, select a quantity of votes, place those votes into a cart, and then pay once through Paystack. After payment is verified, the system applies the votes to the selected nominees and stores complete financial and audit records.

The platform supports the idea that one payment may contain votes for multiple polls, and that those votes may not all remain valid by the time payment is finalized. Because of that, the system supports partial application. If a payment comes in for multiple items and some are no longer valid, valid items are still applied and invalid ones are skipped and recorded.

Core Design Principles
Webhook is the source of truth

The browser never decides whether votes are counted. The frontend may redirect a user after payment, but actual vote application is handled only by the backend after Paystack webhook verification.

Idempotency is mandatory

The same payment reference must never apply the same cart item twice. This is enforced in the vote logs layer so retries, duplicate webhooks, or replay attempts do not create duplicate votes.

Receipts are immutable

Receipts are treated as finalized evidence. Once a receipt reaches a finalized state, its core business data must not change. Only the PDF hash may be set later in a tightly controlled way.

Auditability matters

Important system actions are logged. Payment processing, admin actions, and webhook handling all leave traceable records.

Anonymous public voting

The platform is intentionally built without voter accounts. Voting is public and payment-based, not identity-based.

Technology Stack
Backend

NestJS powers the backend API. It handles public endpoints, admin operations, payment initiation, webhook processing, receipt generation, analytics, and authorization.

Frontend

Next.js App Router powers the frontend. It handles public poll browsing, nominee selection, cart display, receipt display, and admin interface pages.

Database

Oracle Database is the persistent store for all core records: polls, nominees, carts, payments, vote logs, receipts, audit logs, and webhook events.

Payment Provider

Paystack is used for payment initiation and verification. The user is redirected to Paystack for payment, while the backend listens for webhook notifications to confirm and finalize processing.

Authentication

Admin authentication uses JWT with HttpOnly cookies in the frontend architecture. Role-based access control protects admin-only operations.

High-Level System Architecture

The architecture is split into three main layers.

Public frontend

This includes the landing page, poll pages, cart pages, and receipt pages. Users can browse polls, select nominees, choose vote quantities, create carts, and initiate payment.

Backend API

This includes public APIs, payment APIs, admin APIs, receipt APIs, and webhook endpoints. It contains the business logic and is the only layer allowed to finalize votes.

Database

Oracle stores all durable records and enforces many integrity rules using constraints, sequences, triggers, and indexed lookups.

The basic flow is:

User selects poll and nominee on frontend → frontend creates cart via backend → backend initiates Paystack payment → user pays on Paystack → Paystack sends webhook to backend → backend verifies and finalizes payment → votes applied → receipt generated → results updated.

Main Functional Areas
Public Poll Experience

The public side of the platform is responsible for exposing active polls and nominees to end users.

A user can:

view active polls

view nominees inside a poll

choose how many votes to buy

add votes to a cart

review cart contents

proceed to payment

view receipt after payment

The poll page is tied to active poll windows. Poll visibility depends on start date, end date, and current status.

Nominees may inherit price from the parent poll if a nominee-specific price is not defined. This is the main pricing model used by the system.

Cart System

The cart system allows multiple vote selections to be grouped into one payment flow.

Cart model

A cart has:

a numeric internal id

a public cart UUID

a status

a total amount

a created timestamp

Cart item model

Each cart item stores:

cart id

poll id

nominee id

vote quantity

price per vote

subtotal

Cart behavior

A cart starts as pending. Users can add one or more items before payment is initiated. The system calculates item subtotal and total cart amount. Once a verified payment is processed, cart status is updated to either paid or partially applied.

Important design note

The cart UUID is the frontend-safe reference, while the numeric cart id is the database internal identifier. The backend often looks up carts by UUID for public operations.

Payment Flow

The payment subsystem handles initiation, reference generation, amount tracking, and status transitions.

Payment initiation

The backend creates a payment record linked to a cart, generates a Paystack reference, and sends the user to Paystack authorization.

Payment record

A payment stores:

payment id

cart id

paystack reference

amount

status

raw response

paid timestamp

created timestamp

Payment status lifecycle

Typical statuses include:

INITIATED

SUCCESS

FAILED

ABANDONED

PARTIALLY_APPLIED

These statuses support real-world payment behavior. The platform does not assume all successful payment records result in all votes being applied. Partial application is a first-class scenario.

Webhook Processing

Webhook processing is the most important backend responsibility.

Why webhook matters

The user browser is not trusted to confirm payment completion. Only a verified server-to-server webhook may finalize the payment and apply votes.

Webhook responsibilities

When a Paystack webhook arrives, the backend:

validates the webhook signature

parses the event payload

locates the payment record by reference

verifies transaction consistency

moves payment to final state

processes cart items

applies valid votes

records skipped items

updates results

generates or updates receipt data

stores an audit trail in webhook events

Webhook event logging

Each webhook interaction is persisted with fields such as:

provider

route

reference

signature presence

signature validity

processed flag

result

error message

request hash

timing metrics

raw headers and payload

This gives the system a durable operational trace of webhook behavior.

Vote Application and Idempotency

Vote application is not just a simple increment. It is carefully controlled.

Vote application process

For each cart item associated with a finalized payment, the backend checks whether:

the poll is still valid

the nominee belongs to the correct poll

pricing information exists

the cart item has not already been applied for that payment reference

If valid, votes are applied into results. If invalid, the item is marked skipped.

Vote logs

Vote logs are the idempotency core of the system.

Each vote log stores:

cart id

payment id

payment reference

poll id

nominee id

vote quantity

price per vote

subtotal

apply status

skip reason

cart item id

A uniqueness rule on payment reference plus cart item ensures the same cart item is not applied twice for the same payment.

Apply statuses

Typical values:

APPLIED

SKIPPED

This supports both complete success and partial application scenarios.

Results System

The results system stores aggregated counts per poll and nominee combination.

Election results table

Although the business language has shifted from election/candidate to poll/nominee, the database still uses the historical names in many places. ELECTION_RESULTS stores:

poll id

nominee id

vote count

Result updates

Vote counts are updated only after verified payment finalization, not during cart creation and not from the frontend.

Admin live results

Super Admins can view live results through protected admin routes. Public result exposure is intentionally restricted and may be allowed later only after poll closure, depending on business policy.

Receipt System

The receipt system is one of the strongest parts of the platform.

Purpose

A receipt is a durable, verifiable snapshot of what the system believed about a payment and its vote application state at a particular point in time.

Receipt record

A receipt stores:

unique reference

payment id

cart id

status

amount

currency

snapshot json

snapshot hash

PDF version

PDF hash

created timestamp

Snapshot JSON

This contains the full structured receipt data used for rendering and verification, including:

reference

payment information

cart information

line items

summary totals

PDF link

Snapshot hash

The hash protects integrity. It lets the system compare stored receipt content against generated or fetched content to verify consistency.

PDF generation

Receipt PDFs are generated from the stored snapshot, not by re-deriving current live data. That preserves immutability and ensures historical correctness.

Receipt statuses

The schema must allow the backend flow used by the system:

INITIATED

SUCCESS

PARTIALLY_APPLIED

FAILED

Receipt immutability trigger

After finalization, receipts become immutable. The system allows only the tightly controlled setting of PDF_HASH if it was not previously set. Core data changes are blocked.

