This supports post-incident review and operational transparency.

Database Design

The Oracle schema contains the following main tables:

ROLES

Stores admin role definitions.

ADMINS

Stores admin credentials, role mapping, and active state.

AUDIT_LOGS

Stores durable audit events.

ELECTIONS

Stores poll definitions, status windows, and default pricing.

CANDIDATES

Stores nominees belonging to polls and optional nominee-specific pricing.

CARTS

Stores public shopping cart state.

CART_ITEMS

Stores selected poll/nominee vote lines within a cart.

PAYMENTS

Stores payment lifecycle records.

ELECTION_RESULTS

Stores aggregated vote counts.

VOTES

Stores finalized vote records.

VOTE_LOGS

Stores idempotent vote application history.

RECEIPTS

Stores immutable receipt snapshots and hashes.

WEBHOOK_EVENTS

Stores webhook processing audit data.

Sequence Strategy

Because the backend code evolved over time, the schema supports two sequence naming families:

SEQ_* family

Examples:

SEQ_CART_ID

SEQ_PAYMENT_ID

SEQ_ELECTION_ID

*_seq family

Examples:

carts_seq

payments_seq

elections_seq

This is done for backend compatibility because different parts of the application may reference different naming styles.

At deployment time, sequence resync is important. Sequences should be moved to MAX(id) + 1 after any explicit seed inserts to avoid duplicate primary key errors.

Trigger Strategy

The schema uses triggers for numeric primary key assignment on tables where the backend may insert without supplying an id.

Important triggers include:

ROLES_BI

ADMINS_BI

AUDIT_LOGS_BI

ELECTIONS_BI

CANDIDATES_BI

CARTS_BI

PAYMENTS_BI

VOTES_BI

TRG_RECEIPTS_IMMUTABLE

The immutability trigger is especially important to the receipt subsystem.

Pricing Model

The platform uses a two-level pricing model.

Poll-level price

ELECTIONS.DEFAULT_VOTE_PRICE is the default vote price for nominees in that poll.

Nominee-level price

CANDIDATES.VOTE_PRICE overrides the poll default when present.

Effective price resolution

The intended effective price logic is:

candidate vote price if present, otherwise poll default vote price

This matches the original working behavior of the system.

Constraints and Validation Rules

The schema includes key checks to enforce data sanity.

Examples:

admin active state must be Y or N

poll status must be DRAFT, ACTIVE, or ENDED

cart status must be PENDING, PAID, or PARTIALLY_APPLIED

vote quantity must be positive

payment amount must be non-negative

receipt status must support the backend lifecycle

vote apply status must be APPLIED or SKIPPED

These checks are there to catch invalid writes close to the data layer.

Public API Areas

The platform includes public-facing APIs such as:

fetching active polls

fetching nominees by poll

creating cart

fetching cart by UUID

initiating payment

reading receipt by reference

downloading receipt PDF

The exact route layout follows the current frontend/backend proxy structure, but these are the core use cases the public API serves.

Admin API Areas

Admin APIs cover:

